metadata.title: Robinson R22
aws::graph::propositions: Ground Handling of Robinson R22 Helicopter
Robinson R22 helicopters are equipped with wheel mounts toward the rear of the skids.
The wheel mounts are located one on each side of the Robinson R22.
The wheel mounts are for attachment of removable wheels.
The wheels must be removed prior to flight.
The wheel mount brackets are slightly behind the helicopter center of gravity.
When wheels are installed, the Robinson R22 sits nose low.
The wheel assembly has a pivot pin.
The pivot pin is inserted into the skid-mounted bracket.
The pivot pin is rotated over center to lift the rear of the skids about 2 inches.
When the rear skids are lifted, the front of the skids remain on the ground.
The helicopter can be moved by pulling down on the tail.
Pulling down on the tail lifts the front of the skids off the ground.
One person can move the Robinson R22 helicopter.
Moving the Robinson R22 alone is difficult over any distance.
Moving the Robinson R22 alone is difficult on a sloped surface.
Another person can help by pushing on the bracing behind the engine.
Robinson R22 helicopters with flotation attached to the skids must have wheels installed under the skids.
The Mariner is a version of Robinson R22 with flotation attached to the skids.
The Mariner II is a version of Robinson R22 with flotation attached to the skids.
Wheel mount brackets are not accessible when flotation is attached to the skids.

text:
### Ground handling

R22s are equipped with wheel mounts toward the rear of the skids, one on each side, for attachment of removable wheels. The wheels must be removed prior to flight. These brackets are slightly behind the helicopter center of gravity so when the wheels are installed, the helicopter sits nose low.  The wheel assembly has a pivot pin which is inserted into the skid-mounted bracket and then rotated over center to lift the rear of the skids about 2 inches leaving the front of the skids on the ground.  The helicopter can be moved by pulling down on the tail to lift the front of the skids off the ground.  One person can move the helicopter though this is difficult over any distance or on a sloped surface.  Another person can help by pushing on the bracing behind the engine.
R22s with flotation attached to the skids such as the Mariner or Mariner II must have wheels installed under the skids as the bracket is not accessible.
